<TITLE> Malaysia vows tougher crackdown on illegal workers </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 KUALA LUMPUR, Nov 9 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Malaysia promised on Friday to crack down harder on illegal workers, despite criticism that it was already too heavy-handed in expelling poor immigrants. In announcing the tougher stand, Home Minister Radzi Sheikh Ahmad told a ruling-party conference that Malaysia, a country of 26 million people, had tens of thousands of illegal workers. Most illegal immigrants come from neighbouring Indonesia and are rounded up using a volunteer force called Rela, which has been accused of beating some immigrants and stealing from them. Many immigrants have been jailed or caned before being deported. "The enforcement agencies under my ministry, with the assistance of Rela, will step up efforts to hunt down and arrest illegal workers," Radzi told the annual assembly of the main ruling party, the United Malays National Organisation (UMNO). Malaysia's crackdowns on illegal immigrants are an irritant in sometimes brittle relations with Indonesia, a popular source of labour for Malaysia's construction and plantation industries. Malaysia also relies heavily on cheap foreign labour for hotel and restaurant workers and for domestic servants. The government will start publishing weekly tallies of the number of illegal immigrants arrested, Radzi said. Of the 145,000 visas issued on arrival since these were introduced in September last year, about 52,000 had overstayed, he said. Indians had topped the list with 26,000 over-staying. Indonesians do not need visas to enter Malaysia because both countries are members of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations, which allows short visa-free trips among members stat
